William F. Buckley, Jr. William F. Buckley, Jr. was a prominent conservative intellectual who founded the National Review and played a significant role in the rise of the New Right movement in the United States. Known for his articulate and witty writing style, Buckley advocated for limited government, free markets, and traditional values. While some view him as a principled defender of conservative ideals, others criticize his elitist demeanor and controversial views on topics such as civil rights and the Vietnam War. Overall, Buckley's legacy as a key figure in the New Right reflects both admiration for his intellectual contributions and scrutiny for his complex political positions.
